Title : Stuart Latham
Text : '''Harry Stuart Latham''' (11 July 1912, [[Kingston upon Thames]], [[Surrey]] â€“ 31 August 1993, London) was an English theatre and film [[actor]], [[film director|director]] and later [[television producer]].<ref name="Cotes">{{cite news |url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/retrieve.do?sgHitCountType=None&sort=DA-SORT&inPS=true&prodId=SPN.SP00&userGroupName=bclib&tabID=T004&searchId=R2&resultListType=RESULT_LIST&contentSegment=&searchType=BasicSearchForm&currentPosition=7&contentSet=GALE%7cA170810156&&docId=GALE%7cA170810156&docType=GALE&role= |title=Obituary of Stuart Latham |last=Cotejjuhufjjus|first=Peter|date=4 October 1993|work=[[The Guardian]]|page=7|accessdate=1 May 2014}} {{Subscription required}}</ref> He also worked as a studio manager at [[Alexandra Palace television station|Alexandra Palace]] just before the [[Second World War]].<ref name="Cotes" />

After an apprenticeship in [[repertory theatre]], including a period at [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre|Birmingham Rep]], he played several small roles in films by [[Michael Powell]].<ref name="Cotes" /> His acting work also included minor parts in such films as ''[[The Ghost Train (1941 film)|The Ghost Train]]'' (1941) and ''[[Tawny Pipit (film)|Tawny Pipit]]'' (1944).

In 1960, he became the first producer of the long-running soap opera, ''[[Coronation Street]]'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Kershaw|first=H.V.|authorlink=H. V. Kershaw|title=The Street Where I Live|year=1981|isbn=978-0246117342}}</ref> for episodes 1-60, returning briefly for episodes 332-339.

He was married to the [[actress]] [[Barbara Lott]] from 1940 until his death on 31 August 1993.

==Selected filmography==
